The paper deals with lower bounds for distributed and streaming algorithms for spanning forest computation, which are typically studied in the areas of distributed computing (cs.DC), data structures (cs.DS), information theory (cs.IT), network economics (cs.NE), and social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper's focus on lower bounds suggests that it is more likely to be classified under cs.DS or cs.DC, but the use of randomness and probability also makes cs.IT and cs.SI plausible categories. The mention of public randomness and message length in the abstract also suggests cs.NE as a possible category.
